revision.text:
'''Accretion''' is defined as the gradual collection of something over time.<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/accretion Accretion (definition)] Merriam-Webster. Retrieved 14 February 2014.</ref>  In [[meteorology]] or [[atmospheric science]] it is the process of accumulation of frozen water as precipitation over time as it descends through the atmosphere, in particular when an [[ice crystal]] or [[snowflake]] hits a [[supercooled]] [[liquid]] droplet, which then freeze together, increasing the size of the water particle.  The collection of these particles eventually forms [[snow]] or [[hail]] in clouds and depending on lower atmosphere temperatures may become [[rain]], [[Ice pellets|sleet]], or [[graupel]].<ref>[http://nsidc.org/snow/glossary.html National Snow and Ice Data Center]. Retrieved 14 February 2014.</ref> Accretion is the basis for cloud formation and can also be seen as water accumulates on the [[particulates|particulate matter]] and form jet [[contrails]].  This is because water vapor in the air requires [[condensation nuclei]] to form large droplets of solid or liquid water.<ref>[http://coralreefwatch.noaa.gov/satellite/education/workshop/docs/workbook_definitions.pdf NOAA accretion] NOAA. Retrieved 14 February 2014.</ref><ref>[http://nsidc.org/arcticmet/glossary/accretion.html "Accretion (glossary definition)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128071252/http://nsidc.org/arcticmet/glossary/accretion.html |date=January 28, 2010 }}. National Snow and Ice Data Center. Retrieved 16 January 2010. </ref>

