'''Carl Adolf (Adolphe) Otth''' (April 2, 1803, Bern - May 16, 1839) was a Swiss physician and [[naturalist]]. He was the brother of [[mycologist]] [[Gustav Heinrich Otth]] (1806-1874).<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33355944#page/873/mode/1up Taxonomic literature : a selective guide to botanical publications] @ Biodiversity Heritage Library</ref>

In 1822 he studied medicine in Bern, and afterwards attended classes on [[natural history]] in [[Geneva]], where he had as instructors, [[Augustin Pyramus de Candolle]] (1778-1841) and [[Nicolas Charles Seringe]] (1776-1858). He later studied medicine at the Universities of [[University of Kiel|Kiel]] and [[University of Berlin|Berlin]], where in 1828 he received his doctorate. After six months in Paris, he returned to Bern.

In 1836 as a naturalist, he journeyed to [[Dauphiné]] and [[Provence]] in France, to the [[Balearic Islands]] and also to [[Algeria]]. From these travels he collected a large number of insect, reptile and [[amphibian]] species. In 1837 he was the first to describe the frog genus ''[[Discoglossus]]'' based on studies of the [[Discoglossus pictus|Mediterranean painted frog]] (''Discoglossus pictus'').

In 1838 he published a book with thirty [[lithograph]]s based on a trip to [[Algiers]], titled ''Esquisses africaines, dessinées pendant un voyage a Alger et lithographiées par Adolphe Otth''. In 1839 during a journey to the Middle East, he died in [[Jerusalem]] at the age of 36.
