{{Infobox scientist |name = Richard S. Boardman |image = |image_size = 200px |caption = |birth_date = 1923 |birth_place = |death_date = 2011 |death_place = |residence = Saratosa, FL |citizenship = |nationality = [[United States|American]] |ethnicity = |field = [[Paleontology]] |work_institutions = |alma_mater = University of Illinois |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = [[bryozoans]], [[morphology (biology)|morphology]] |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} '''Richard S. Boardman''' was an [[United States|American]] [[paleontologist]] and curator of the Department of Paleobiology at the United States National Museum (now the [[National Museum of Natural History]]). Boardman worked for the museum from 1957 to 1985 and subsequently became a founding member of the [[International Bryozoology Association]] (IBA).<ref name="SIA archives">[http://siarchives.si.edu/collections/siris_sic_8925 Richard S. Boardman] at the SIA archives.</ref> Boardman is best known for the hard/soft thin-sectioning technique that he developed in order to compare the internal morphology of living and fossilized bryozoans which have revealed new information about bryozoan life history.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scholz|first=Andrej Ernst, Priska Schäfer, Joachim|title=Bryozoan Studies 2010|date=2012|publisher=Springer Verlag|location=Berlin|isbn=978-3642164101|pages=xv-xvi}}</ref>
