'''Sidney Hugh Reynolds''' DSc, FGS (18 December 1867 &ndash; 20 August 1949) was an English geologist, palaeontologist, and zoologist.<ref name=WoodwardBio>{{cite book|title=Arthur Smith Woodward: His Life and Influence on Modern Vertebrate Paeolontology|year=2016|page=105|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4EafCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA105|editor=Johanson, Z.|editor2=Barrett P.M.|editor3=Richter, M.|editor4=Smith, M.|publisher=Geological Society, London|series=Special Publication 430|postscript=; 362 pages; hbk|isbn=978-1-86239-741-5}}</ref><ref name=UCambridge>{{acad|name=Reynolds, Sidney Hugh|id=RNLS886SH}}</ref>

Reynolds was born in [[Brighton]]. He was educated at [[Marlborough College]] and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], where he received B.A. (Nat.
Sci. [[Tripos]], Pt I, 1st Class) 1889; (Pt II, 1st Class, 1890); M.A. 1894; Sc.D. 1913.<ref name=UCambridge/> He was acting professor of zoology at [[Madras Christian College]] in 1891–1892 and in 1897–1898.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reynolds, Sidney Hugh|journal=Who's Who|year=1919|page= 2065|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015047639912;view=1up;seq=2107}}</ref> At the [[University of Bristol]] he was a lecturer from 1894 to 1899, an assistant professor of zoology and geology from 1899 to 1900, a professor of zoology and geology from 1900 to 1910, and a professor of geology from 1910 to 1933, when he retired as professor emeritus.<ref name=UCambridge/> He then became the curator of the [[Stroud District]] Cowle Museum.<ref name=WoodwardBio/>

He was the president of Section "G" of the [[British Association]] in 1926.<ref name=UCambridge/> He was awarded the [[Lyell Medal]] in 1928. (In the same year [[William Dickson Lang]] was also awarded the Lyell Medal for work done independently.) He died in [[Clifton, Bristol]], aged 81.

